// Package cm (container manager) is responsible for managing containers
// running on a node. It provides the core abstractions for resource isolation,
// allocation, and enforcement within the kubelet.
//
// # Key Responsibilities
//
// The container manager handles several critical functions:
//
//   - Cgroup Management: Creates, updates, and destroys cgroups for pods and
//     containers. Supports both cgroup v1 and cgroup v2, with systemd or cgroupfs
//     as the cgroup driver.
//
//   - QoS Enforcement: Manages Quality of Service (QoS) class containers
//     (Guaranteed, Burstable, BestEffort) through the QOSContainerManager.
//     Enforces resource limits at the QoS level to ensure proper resource
//     isolation between different service tiers.
//
//   - Resource Allocation: Tracks and allocates compute resources (CPU, memory,
//     devices) to containers, ensuring pods receive their requested resources
//     while respecting node capacity and allocatable limits.
//
//   - Node Allocatable: Computes and enforces node allocatable resources by
//     accounting for system reserved, kube reserved, and eviction thresholds.
//
//   - Device Plugin Integration: Coordinates with device plugins through the
//     devicemanager subpackage to allocate extended resources like GPUs and
//     other hardware accelerators.
//
//   - Pod Lifecycle: Manages container lifecycle events including creation,
//     resource updates, and cleanup through the InternalContainerLifecycle
//     interface.
//
// # Core Interfaces
//
// ContainerManager is the primary interface that the kubelet uses to interact
// with this package. It provides methods for starting the manager, creating
// pod containers, retrieving node capacity, and coordinating with resource
// managers.
//
// CgroupManager provides the low-level interface for cgroup operations including
// Create, Destroy, Update, and resource configuration. It abstracts differences
// between cgroup v1 and v2, as well as systemd vs cgroupfs drivers.
//
// PodContainerManager handles pod-level cgroup management, creating and managing
// the cgroup hierarchy for individual pods based on their QoS class.
//
// QOSContainerManager manages the top-level QoS cgroups (Guaranteed, Burstable,
// BestEffort) and periodically updates their resource constraints.
//
// # Subpackages
//
// The cm package includes several specialized subpackages:
//
//   - cpumanager: Manages CPU affinity and exclusive CPU allocation for
//     containers with integer CPU requests. Supports static and none policies.
//
//   - memorymanager: Handles NUMA-aware memory allocation and memory pinning
//     for containers. Supports static, none, and best-effort policies.
//
//   - topologymanager: Coordinates resource allocation decisions across CPU,
//     memory, and device managers to achieve optimal NUMA locality. Supports
//     none, best-effort, restricted, and single-numa-node policies.
//
//   - devicemanager: Implements the device plugin framework, managing the
//     lifecycle of device plugins and allocating device resources to containers.
//
//   - dra: Implements Dynamic Resource Allocation (DRA) for managing dynamic
//     resources through resource claims and resource drivers.
//
//   - containermap: Provides data structures for mapping containers to their
//     runtime identifiers.
//
// # Platform Support
//
// The container manager has platform-specific implementations:
//
//   - Linux: Full implementation with cgroup management, QoS enforcement,
//     CPU/memory managers, and all resource isolation features. Supports both
//     cgroup v1 (deprecated) and cgroup v2.
//
//   - Windows: Limited implementation focused on capacity reporting and device
//     management. Windows uses Job Objects instead of cgroups for resource
//     isolation, with optional CPU and memory affinity support through the
//     WindowsCPUAndMemoryAffinity feature gate.
//
// # Cgroup Versions
//
// On Linux, the container manager supports both cgroup v1 and cgroup v2:
//
//   - Cgroup v1: Uses separate hierarchies for different resource controllers
//     (cpu, memory, cpuset, etc.). Support is deprecated and will be removed
//     in a future release.
//
//   - Cgroup v2: Uses a unified hierarchy with all controllers mounted together.
//     This is the recommended configuration and provides better resource
//     isolation and accounting.
//
// # Usage
//
// The container manager is created and started by the kubelet during
// initialization. It must be started before pods can be created on the node.
// The kubelet interacts with the container manager through the ContainerManager
// interface to manage pod resources throughout their lifecycle.
package cm

